      rw [h4]
      apply Measurable.comp
      · -- apply Real.toNNReal
        apply measurable_real_toNNReal
      · -- apply neg
        apply measurable_neg
        apply measurable_id
```

Wait, this is not correct. `g₂` is `fun x ↦ Real.toNNReal (- RCLike.re (g x))`.
So `g₂ x = Real.toNNReal (- RCLike.re (g x))`.
This is a composition of `Real.toNNReal` and `neg` applied to `RCLike.re (g x)`.
`RCLike.re (g x)` is a real number.
So `g₂ x = Real.toNNReal (- (RCLike.re (g x)))`.

Let's fix this.

```tactics
have h3 : Measurable g₂ := by
  have h4 : g₂ = fun x => Real.toNNReal (- RCLike.re (g x)) := by rfl
  rw [h4]
  apply Measurable.comp
  · -- apply Real.toNNReal
    apply measurable_real_toNNReal
  · -- apply neg
    apply measurable_neg
    apply -- apply RCLike.re
      -- need to show RCLike.re is measurable
      -- g is strongly measurable
      -- so g x is measurable
      -- RCLike.re is continuous
      -- so RCLike.re (g x) is measurable
      -- Real.toNNReal is measurable
      -- so neg (RCLike.re (g x)) is measurable
      -- Real.toNNReal is measurable
      -- so Real.toNNReal (neg (RCLike.re (g x))) is measurable
```

Wait, this is getting complicated. Let's simplify.

`g` is `α → 𝕂`, `g` is `stronglyMeasurable_g : StronglyMeasurable g`.
`g₂` is `fun x ↦ Real.toNNReal (- RCLike.re (g x))`.
`g₂` is `α → NNReal`.

`g₂` is the composition of `Real.toNNReal` with the negation of the real part of `g`.
`RCLike.re (g x)` is a real number.
`neg (RCLike.re (g x))` is a real number.
`Real.toNNReal (neg (RCLike.re (g x)))` is a `NNReal` number.

`g₂` is `Measurable` because `g` is `StronglyMeasurable` (so `g x` is `AESTronglyMeasurable`), `RCLike.re` is `continuous` (so `RCLike.re (g x)` is `AESTronglyMeasurable`), `neg` is `continuous` (so `neg (RCLike.re (g x))` is `AESTronglyMeasurable`), `Real.toNNReal` is `continuous` (so `Real.toNNReal (neg (RCLike.re (g x)))` is `AESTronglyMeasurable`).

